Q.1) Using grep, Find all the records where the profession is "developer".
Ans - grep -i 'developer' sample.csv

Q.2) Using awk , Display only those lines where the salary is above 90000.
Ans - awk -F',' '$5 > 90000' sample.csv

Q.3) Using awk , Print firstname, lastname, and salary of all "police officer" employees.
Ans - awk -F',' '{print $2,$3,$5}' sample.txt

Q.4) Using awk, Find the total salary of all workers (profession = worker).
Ans - awk -F',' '$NF=="worker" { sum += $5 } END { print "The total salary of the workers is " sum }'

Q.5) Using awk, Print the email addresses of all people whose salary is less than 50000.
Ans - awk -F',' 'NR>1 && $5 < 50000 { print $4 } ' sample.csv

Q.6) Using awk, Count how many employees exist for each profession.
Ans - awk -F',' 'NR>1 { count[$6]++ } END { for(p in count) print p, count[p] }' sample.csv
# here count is not any module or function its an array name , count[$6]++ counts how many times each profession appears.

Q.7) Using sed, Replace all occurrences of “worker” with “labour” in the file (without modifying other professions).
Ans -  sed 's/worker/labour/' sample.csv , sed -i 's/worker/labour/' sample.csv #to modify the file 

Q.8) Using sed, Remove all lines where the profession is “doctor”.
Ans - sed '/doctor/d' sample.csv

Q.9) Using awk, Print only those records where firstname starts with the letter ‘M’.
Ans -  awk -F',' '$2 ~ /^M/' filename.csv















